cvterm.definition: MsrA is an ABC-efflux pump expressed to Staphylococcus species that confers resistance to erythromycin and streptogramin B antibiotics. It is associated with plasmid DNA.

cvterm.name: mutant porin Omp36 with reduced permeability to antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Mutant forms of the porin Omp36 result in reduced permeability to antibiotics.

cvterm.name: glycopeptide resistance gene cluster VanD
cvterm.definition: Homologous to vanA, contains a D-Ala-D-Lac ligase. This cluster is constitutively expressed due to a dysfunctional D-ala-D-ala ligase.nnGene orientation: vanRSYHDX

cvterm.name: emrY
cvterm.definition: ErmY is a multidrug transport that moves substrates across the inner membrane of the Gram-negative E. coli. It is a homolog of ErmB.

cvterm.name: glycopeptide resistance gene cluster VanF
cvterm.definition: Homologous to vanA, contains a D-Ala-D-Lac ligase.

cvterm.name: glycopeptide resistance gene cluster VanM
cvterm.definition: Homologous to vanA, contains a D-Ala-D-Lac ligase.

cvterm.name: glycopeptide resistance gene cluster VanG
cvterm.definition: Homologous to VanC, contains a D-Ala-D-Ser ligase.nnGene orientation: vanRSYWGYT

cvterm.name: ErmC'
cvterm.definition: ErmC' is ErmC but without the leader peptide and therefore expression is constitutive. Originally found on the plasmid pIM13 from Bacillus subtilis. It confers the MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: glycopeptide resistance gene cluster VanE
cvterm.definition: Homologous to VanC, contains a D-Ala-D-Ser ligase.

cvterm.name: glycopeptide resistance gene cluster VanL
cvterm.definition: Homologous to VanC, contains a D-Ala-D-Ser ligase.nnGene orientation: vanL(X/Y)TmTrRS

cvterm.name: sigma factor conferring resistance to rifampin
cvterm.definition: When bound to different sigma factors, RNA-polymerase may possess an altered sensitivity to rifampin-mediated inhibition.

cvterm.name: bla operon
cvterm.definition: The bla operon is composed of blaZ/blaR1/blaI.

cvterm.name: marA
cvterm.definition: In the presence of antibiotic stress, E. coli overexpresses the global activator protein MarA, which besides inducing MDR efflux pump AcrAB, also down- regulates synthesis of the porin OmpF.

cvterm.name: emrE
cvterm.definition: EmrE is a small multidrug transporter that functions as a homodimer and that couples the efflux of small polyaromatic cations from the cell with the import of protons down an electrochemical gradient.

cvterm.name: porin OmpF
cvterm.definition: In the presence of antibiotic stress, E. coli overexpresses the global activator protein MarA, which besides inducing MDR efflux pump AcrAB, also down- regulates synthesis of the porin OmpF.

cvterm.name: ADP-ribosylation of antibiotic conferring resistance
cvterm.definition: The inactivation of antibiotics by the enzymatic addition of ADP-ribose from NAD+.

cvterm.name: linezolid resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genes conferring resistance to linezolids.

cvterm.name: mec operon
cvterm.definition: The mac operon is composed of mecA/mecR1/mecI.

cvterm.name: brodimoprim
cvterm.definition: Brodimoprim is a structural derivative of trimethoprim and an inhibitor of bacterial dihydrofolate reductase. The 4-methoxy group of trimethoprim is replaced with a bromine atom.

cvterm.name: gene modulating permeability to antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Genes directly or indirectly reducing overall permeability to antibiotics.

cvterm.name: fosfomycin resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genes conferring resistance to fosfomycin.

cvterm.name: LinA
cvterm.definition: LinA and variants LnuC, LnuD are similar to aminoglycoside nucleotidylyl transferases (ANTs)

cvterm.name: antibiotic resistant DNA topoisomerase subunit gyrA
cvterm.definition: Point mutations in gyrA confer antibiotic resistance by preventing drugs from binding the alpha-subunit of gyrase, essential for DNA supercoiling.

cvterm.name: antibiotic resistant DNA topoisomerase subunit parC
cvterm.definition: Point mutations in parC confer antibiotic resistance by preventing drugs from binding the parC subunit of topoisomerase IV, essential for DNA decatanation and relaxation.

cvterm.name: LinB
cvterm.definition: LinB and variant LnuF are similar to the beta-subunit of DNA polymerase (Pol beta)

cvterm.name: cephem
cvterm.definition: Cephems have a six-membered dihydrothiazine ring with a sulfur atom and double bond fused with its beta-lactam ring. This group includes the cephalosporins and cephamycins, the latter containing an additional alpha-methoxy group.

cvterm.name: sulfonamide
cvterm.definition: Sulfonamides are broad spectrum, synthetic antibiotics that contain the sulfonamide group. Sulfonamides inhibit dihydropteroate synthase, which catalyzes the conversion of p-aminobenzoic acid to dihydropteroic acid as part of the tetrahydrofolic acid biosynthetic pathway. Tetrahydrofolic acid is essential for folate synthesis, a precursor of many nucleotides and amino acids. Many sulfamides are taken with trimethoprim, an inhibitor of dihydrofolate reductase, also disturbing the trihydrofolic acid synthesis pathway.

cvterm.name: tetroxoprim
cvterm.definition: Tetroxoprim is a trimethoprim derivative that inhibits bacterial dihydrofolate reductase.

cvterm.name: phosphonopyruvate decarboxylase
cvterm.definition: Stabilizes the C-P bond in phosphonopyruvate formed by phophoenolpyruvate mutase by catalyzing the self-removal of the carboxyl group.

cvterm.name: lsa
cvterm.definition: Lsa ("lincosamide and streptogramin A resistance

cvterm.name: emrD
cvterm.definition: EmrD is a multidrug transporter from the Major Facilitator Superfamily (MFS) primarily found in Escherichia coli. EmrD couples efflux of amphipathic compounds with proton import across the plasma membrane.

cvterm.name: macrolide resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genes or their products conferring resistance to macrolide antibiotics.

cvterm.name: macrolide phosphotransferase (2')-I
cvterm.definition: The mphA gene encodes for resistance enzyme MPH(2')-I which preferentially inactivate 14-membered macrolides (e.g.erythromycin, telithromycin, roxithromycin) over 16-membered macrolides (e.g.tylosin, spiramycin). It phosphorylates macrolides at 2'-OH hydroxyl of desosamine sugar of macrolides in a GTP-dependent manner.

cvterm.name: AAC(1)
cvterm.definition: Acetylation of paromomycin, and apramycin, on the amino group at position 1.

cvterm.name: macrolide phosphotransferase (2')-II
cvterm.definition: The mphB gene encodes for MPH(2')-II. This enzymes phosphorylates 14-membered and 16-membered macrolides. It phosphorylates macrolides in GTP- dependent manner at 2'-OH hydroxyl of desosamine sugar of macrolides.

cvterm.name: macrolide phosphotransferase C
cvterm.definition: The mphC gene was identified from Staphylococcus aureus. This gene shows similarity to mphB gene from Escherchia coli.

cvterm.name: macrolide esterase
cvterm.definition: Hydrolytic enzymes that cleave the macrocycle lactone ring of macrolide antibiotics.

cvterm.name: hydrolysis of macrolide macrocycle lactone ring
cvterm.definition: Hydrolysis of the the macrocycle lactone ring of macrolide antibiotics.

cvterm.name: AAC(3)
cvterm.definition: Acetylation of the aminoglycoside antibiotic on the amino group at position 3.

cvterm.name: sulfadiazine
cvterm.definition: Sulfadiazine is a potent inhibitor of dihydropteroate synthase, interfering with the tetrahydrofolic biosynthesis pathway. Tetrahydrofolic acid is essential for folate synthesis, a precursor to many nucleotides and amino acids.

cvterm.name: sulfadimidine
cvterm.definition: Sulfadimidine is an alkaline sulfonamide antibiotic that inhibits dihydropteroate synthase, and enzyme in the tetrahydrofolic acid biosynthesis pathway. This interferes with the production of folate, which is a precursor to many amino acids and nucleotides.

cvterm.name: ErmE
cvterm.definition: ErmE is a dimethyltransferase that confers the MLSb phenotype in the producing (erythromycin) organism, Saccharopolyspora erythraea.

cvterm.name: sulfadoxine
cvterm.definition: Sulfadoxine is an inhibitor of dihydropteroate synthase, interfering with the tetrahydrofolic biosynthesis pathway. Tetrahydrofolic acid is essential for folate synthesis, a precursor to many nucleotides and amino acids.

cvterm.name: rRNA with mutation conferring antibiotic resistance
cvterm.definition: Single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) in rRNA can confer antibiotic resistance to drugs that target the bacterial ribosome.

cvterm.name: sulfamethoxazole
cvterm.definition: Sulfamethoxazole is a sulfonamide antibiotic usually taken with trimethoprim, a diaminopyrimidine antibiotic. Sulfamethoxazole inhibits dihydropteroate synthase, essential to tetrahydrofolic acid biosynthesis. This pathway generates compounds used in the synthesis of many amino acids and nucleotides.

cvterm.name: sulfisoxazole
cvterm.definition: Sulfisoxazole is an inhibitor of dihydropteroate synthase, interfering with the tetrahydrofolic biosynthesis pathway. Tetrahydrofolic acid is essential for folate synthesis, a precursor to many nucleotides and amino acids.

cvterm.name: macrolide phosphotransferase (MPH)
cvterm.definition: Macrolide phosphotransferases (MPH) are enzymes encoded by macrolide phosphotransferase genes (mph genes). These enzymes phosphorylate macrolides in GTP dependent manner at 2'-OH of desosamine sugar thereby inactivating them. Characterized MPH's are differentiated based on their substrate specificity.

cvterm.name: 23S rRNA with mutation conferring antibiotic resistance
cvterm.definition: Point mutations in bacterial 23S rRNA from the large ribosome subunit that confer resistance to antibiotics. Reference sequence and mutations refer to S. aureus.

cvterm.name: iclaprim
cvterm.definition: Iclaprim is a bactericidal compound that inhibits dihydrofolate reductase. It is used against clinically important Gram-positive pathogens, including methicillin-sensitive Staphylococcus aureus and methicillin-resistant S. aureus.

cvterm.name: linearization of antibiotic conferring resistance
cvterm.definition: Genes that confer antibiotic resistance by hydrolyzing bonds to linearize and deactivate antibiotics.

cvterm.name: AAC(2')
cvterm.definition: Acetylation of the aminoglycoside antibiotic on the amino group at position 2'.

cvterm.name: fosfomycin inactivation enzyme
cvterm.definition: Enzymes that inactivate fosfomycin by chemical modification.

cvterm.name: Tap-like efflux pump
cvterm.definition: Efflux pump proteins contained within Mycobacterial genomes which confer resistance to a number of different antibiotics including aminoglycosides, and tetracyclines.

cvterm.name: EmrAB-TolC
cvterm.definition: EmrAB-TolC is a multidrug efflux system found in E. coli. EmrB is the electrochemical-gradient powered transporter; EmrA is the linker; and TolC is the outer membrane channel. It confers resistance to nalidixic acid and thiolactomycin.

cvterm.name: AAC(6')
cvterm.definition: Acetylation of the aminoglycoside antibiotic on the amino group at position 6'.

cvterm.name: Alignment Reference
cvterm.definition: An example polypeptide sequence used as a reference point in multiple sequence alignment and mapping of single nucleotide polymorphisms that confer antibiotic resistance (AR-SNP).

cvterm.name: ErmA
cvterm.definition: ErmA confers the MLSb phenotype. Similar to ErmC, Expression of ErmA is inducible by erythromycin. The leader peptide causes attenuation of the mRNA and stabilizes the structure preventing further translation. When erythromycin is present, it binds the leader peptide causing a change in conformation allowing for the expression of ErmA.

cvterm.name: fosfomycin phosphotransferase
cvterm.definition: In the presence of ATP and magnesium (II), fosfomycin gets phosphorylated at the phosphate group resulting in a diphosphate group which inactivates the antibiotic.

cvterm.name: EreA
cvterm.definition: EreA is an erythromycin esterase that hydrolyses the drug's lactone ring.

cvterm.name: mosaic antibiotic resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Definition needed.

cvterm.name: EreB
cvterm.definition: EreB is an erythromycin esterase-like protein that hydrolyses the drug's lactone ring.

cvterm.name: HMM bit-score
cvterm.definition: A bit-score cut-off for significant HMM hit.

cvterm.name: fluoroquinolone acetyltransferase
cvterm.definition: Variants of aminoglycoside acetyltransferase (AAC) that have gained the ability to modify fluoroquinolones with free nitrogen on a piperazine moiety such as ciprofloxacin

cvterm.name: vanC
cvterm.definition: VanC is a D-Ala-D-Ala ligase that can synthesize D-Ala-D-Ser, an alternative substrate for peptidoglycan synthesis that reduces vancomycin binding affinity. It is specific to Enterococcus gallinarum and E. casseliflavus, providing intrinsic resistance.

cvterm.name: MtrCDE
cvterm.definition: The mtr (multiple transferable resistance) system of Neisseria gonorrhoeae confers resistance to many hydrophobic agents including antibiotics, fatty-acids and detergents. MtrCDE is homologous to AcrAB-TolC, where MtrC is the membrane fusion protein, MtrD is the inner membrane transporter, and MtrE is the outer membrane channel protein.

cvterm.name: antibiotic resistant DNA topoisomerase subunit
cvterm.definition: Many drugs target topoisomerases to inhibit DNA synthesis. Resistant DNA topoisomerase subunits prevent antibiotic binding and thus confer resistance.

cvterm.name: vanT
cvterm.definition: VanT is a membrane bound serine racemase, converting L-serine to D-serine. It is associated with VanC, which incorporated D-serine into D-Ala-D-Ser terminal end of peptidoglycan subunits that have a decreased binding affinity with vancomycin. It was isolated in Enterococcus gallinarum.

cvterm.name: EmrKY-TolC
cvterm.definition: EmrKY is a homolog of EmrAB found in E. coli. Together with TolC, it is a tripartite multidrug transporter.

cvterm.name: ErmB
cvterm.definition: ErmB confers the MLSb phenotype. Similar to ErmC, expression of ErmB is inducible by erythromycin. The leader peptide causes attenuation of the mRNA and stabilizes the structure preventing further translation. When erythromycin is present, it binds the leader peptide causing a change in conformation allowing for the expression of ErmB.

cvterm.name: streptogramin Vgb lyase
cvterm.definition: Vgb lyase inactivates type B streptogramins by cleaving the ester bond, resulting in linearization.

cvterm.name: mexA
cvterm.definition: MexA is the membrane fusion protein of the MexAB-OprM multidrug efflux complex.

cvterm.name: mexB
cvterm.definition: MexB is the inner membrane multidrug exporter of the efflux complex MexAB-OprM.

cvterm.name: oprM
cvterm.definition: OprM is an outer membrane factor protein found in Pseudomonas aeruginosa. It is part of the MexAB-OprM complex.

cvterm.name: FosC
cvterm.definition: An enzyme thought to phosphorylate the phosphate group of fosfomycin using ATP specifically.

cvterm.name: antibiotic target replacement protein
cvterm.definition: Alternate proteins that have the same functions as other antibiotic target proteins, but are structurally different and thus resistant to antibiotics. These can replace the activity of other antibiotic-sensitive proteins in the presence of antibiotics.

cvterm.name: azidamfenicol
cvterm.definition: Azidamfenicol is a water soluble derivative of chloramphenicol, sharing the same mode of action of inhibiting peptide synthesis by interacting with the 23S RNA of the 50S ribosomal subunit.

cvterm.name: rifampin resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genetic determinants which confer resistance to rifampin.

cvterm.name: AcrAB-TolC
cvterm.definition: AcrAB-TolC is a tripartite RND efflux system that confers resistance to many antibiotics in Gram-negative bacteria. The system spans the cell membrane (AcrB) and the outer-membrane (TolC), and is linked together in the periplasm by AcrA.

cvterm.name: chloramphenicol
cvterm.definition: Chloramphenicol is a bacteriostatic antimicrobial originally derived from the bacterium Streptomyces venezuelae. It was the first antibiotic to be manufactured synthetically on a large scale. It functions by inhibiting peptidyl transferase activity of the bacterial ribosome, binding to A2451 and A2452 residues in the 23S rRNA of the 50S ribosomal subunit and preventing peptide bond formation.

cvterm.name: MexAB-OprM
cvterm.definition: MexAB-OprM is a multidrug efflux protein expressed in the Gram-negative Pseudomonas aeruginosa. MexA is the membrane fusion protein; MexB is the inner membrane transporter; and OprM is the outer membrane channel. MexAB-OprM is associated with resistance to fluoroquinolones, chloramphenicol, erythromycin, azithromycin, novobiocin, and certain N2-lactams.

cvterm.name: phenicol
cvterm.definition: Phenicols are broad spectrum bacteriostatic antibiotics acting on bacterial protein synthesis. More specifically, the phenicols block peptide elongation by binding to the peptidyltansferase centre of the 70S ribosome.

cvterm.name: streptogramin biosynthesis
cvterm.definition: Biosynthesis of streptoramin antibiotics.

cvterm.name: streptogramin B biosynthesis
cvterm.definition: Type B streptogramins are cyclic hexa- or hepta-depsipeptides produced by NRPSs in Streptomyces. The NRPS contains 6 or 7 modules arranged on one or more genes. SnbA catalyzes the activation of the first residue, 3-hydroxypicolynic acid. SnbC then activates and incorporates threonine and aminobutyric acid. Lastly, SnbDE activates and incoporates the last four amino acids. The thioesterase domain is responsible for peptide cyclization, and it is located at the end of the assembly line.

cvterm.name: rifampin ADP-ribosyltransferase (Arr)
cvterm.definition: Enzyme responsible for the ADP-ribosylative inactivation of rifampin at the 23-OH position using NAD+.

cvterm.name: norA
cvterm.definition: NorA is a multidrug efflux pump in Staphylococcus aureus that confers resistance to fluoroquinolones and other structurally unrelated antibiotics like acriflavine. It shares 30% similarity with NorA, and is a structural homolog of Bmr of Bacillus subtilis. It is regulated by arlRS and mgrA, the latter also known as NorR.

cvterm.name: Erm(37)
cvterm.definition: Erm(37) is found in Mycobacterium species and confers the MLSb phenotype. In addition to methylation of A2058 this Erm methylates adjacent adenosines (A2057 and A2059) as well.

cvterm.name: glycopeptide biosynthesis
cvterm.definition: Synthesis of glycopeptide antibiotics.

cvterm.name: Actinoplanes teichomyceticus teicoplanin gene cluster
cvterm.definition: Biosynthesis of teicoplanin by Actinoplanes teichomyceticus

cvterm.name: chloramphenicol resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genes conferring resistance to chloramphenicol.

cvterm.name: sulfonamide resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genes conferring resistance to sulfonamide antibiotics.

cvterm.name: sul1
cvterm.definition: Sul1 is a sulfonamide resistant dihydropteroate synthase of Gram-negative bacteria. It is linked to other resistance genes of class 1 integrons.

cvterm.name: sul2
cvterm.definition: Sul2 is a sulfonamide resistant dihydropteroate synthase of Gram-negative bacteria, usually found on small plasmids.

cvterm.name: sul3
cvterm.definition: Sul3 is a sulfonamide resistant dihydropteroate synthase similar to Sul1 and Sul2. Its resistance gene was found encoded in E. coli plasmid DNA of sulfonamide resistant isolates.

cvterm.name: quinolone resistance protein (Qnr)
cvterm.definition: Qnrs are pentapeptide repeat proteins that mimic DNA and protect the cell from the activity of fluoroquinolone antibiotics

cvterm.name: norB
cvterm.definition: NorB is a multidrug efflux pump in Staphylococcus aureus that confers resistance to fluoroquinolones and other structurally unrelated antibiotics like tetracycline. It shares 30% similarity with NorB, and is a structural homolog of Blt of Bacillus subtilis. It is regulated by mgrA, also known as NorR.

cvterm.name: FomA
cvterm.definition: In the presence of ATP and magnesium (II), fosfomycin gets phosphorylated at the phosphate group resulting in a diphosphate group which inactivates the antibiotic.

cvterm.name: rifampin glycosyltransferase
cvterm.definition: The enzymatic inactivation of rifampin by glycosylation at the 23-OH position.

cvterm.name: rifampin phosphotransferase
cvterm.definition: The enzymatic inactivation of rifampin by phosphorylation at the 21-OH position.

cvterm.name: rifampin monooxygenase
cvterm.definition: Enzyme responsible for the decolorization of rifampin by monoxygenation.

cvterm.name: mupirocin resistant isoleucyl-tRNA synthetase
cvterm.definition: Mupirocin inhibits protein synthesis by interfering with isoleucyl-tRNA synthetase (ileS). While mutations in ileS can confer low-level mupirocin resistance, high level resistance is conferred by the presence of alternative isoleucyl-tRNA syntheses.

cvterm.name: qepA
cvterm.definition: QepA is a plasmid-mediated fluoroquinolone efflux pump found in E. coli. It is regulated by sox genes, also known as global stress regulators.

cvterm.name: FomB
cvterm.definition: An enzyme which on its own cannot provide fosfomycin resistance, however in conjunction with FomA, it leads to the formation of fosfomycin with three phosphates total, which makes it inactive.

cvterm.name: hydroxylation of antibiotic conferring resistance
cvterm.definition: Inactivation of an antibiotic via introduction a hydroxyl group (-OH).

cvterm.name: gene modulating antibiotic efflux
cvterm.definition: Genes that directly or indirectly change rates of antibiotic efflux.

cvterm.name: fluoroquinolone resistant DNA topoisomerase
cvterm.definition: Fluoroquinolones inhibit type II and type IV topoisomerases (2 strand breaking enzymes) such as GyrA/GyrB and ParC/ParE. Point mutations in the associated gyrA and parC genes, in particular in the 'quinolone resistance determining region' (QRDR), give rise to resistance to the class.

cvterm.name: vat acetyltransferase
cvterm.definition: Virginiamycin acetyltransferases catalyze the transfer of an acetyl group from acetylCoA to the secondary alcohol of streptogramin A. Vat enzymes belong to the hexapeptide repeat family of acyltransferases.

cvterm.name: polymyxin B
cvterm.definition: Polymyxin B is mixture of mostly polymyxins B1 and B2, mainly used for resistant gram-negative infections. They are polypeptides with cationic detergent action on cell membranes.

cvterm.name: streptogramin A biosynthesis
cvterm.definition: Type A streptogramins are produced by a hybrid NRPS/PKS composed of 8 NRPS modules and 2 PKS modules.

cvterm.name: thiamphenicol
cvterm.definition: Derivative of Chloramphenicol. The nitro group (-NO2) is substituted by a sulfomethyl group (-SO2CH3).

cvterm.name: aminocoumarin resistant parE
cvterm.definition: ParE is a subunit of topoisomerase IV, which decatenates and relaxes DNA to allow access to genes for transcription or translation. Point mutations in ParE prevent anticoumarin antibiotics from inhibiting DNA synthesis, thus conferring resistance.

cvterm.name: macrolide glycosyltransferase
cvterm.definition: Macrolide glycosyltransferases are enzymes encoded by macrolide glycosyltransferase genes and inactivate macrolides by glycosylating them at 2'-OH of desosamine sugar moiety. They are predominantly found in macrolide producers and are also found in non-producers and are used as a resistance mechanism. Different variants of this enzyme has been reported.

cvterm.name: fosfomycin biosynthesis
cvterm.definition: Biosynthesis of fosfomycin.

cvterm.name: msbA
cvterm.definition: MsbA is a lipid flipase that is a model for ABC drug resistance efflux. It does not confer antibiotic resistance itself.

cvterm.name: florfenicol
cvterm.definition: Florfenicol is a fluorine derivative of chloramphenicol, where the nitro group (-NO2) is substituted by a sulfomethyl group (-SO2CH3) and the hydroxyl group (-OH), by a fluorine group (-F). The action mechanism is the same as chloramphenicol's, where the antibiotic binds to the 23S RNA of the 50S subunit of bacterial ribosomes to inhibit protein synthesis.

cvterm.name: mgt glycosyltransferase
cvterm.definition: The mgt gene encodes for macrolide glycosyltransferase found in Streptomyces lividans. This enzyme inactivates macrolides using UDP-glucose as a cofactor. Its optimal substrates are lankamycin, calcomycin, rosaramicin, methymycin, and pikromycin, while interactions with erythomycin, oldeandomycin, azithromycin, and tylosin were weaker. It is inactive against spiramycin and carbomycin.

cvterm.name: gimA glycosyltransferase
cvterm.definition: gimA gene codes for a glycosyltransferase found in Streptomyces ambofaciens, natural producer of macrolide spiramycin. Chalcomycin, methymycin, tylosin, pikromycin, rosaramicin, oleandomycin, josamycin, and carbomycin are preferred substrates of gimA glycosyltransferase, while erythromycin and spiramycin have notably low binding affinities. GimA may be able to inactivate spiramycin precursors.

cvterm.name: mutant porin PIB (por) with reduced permeability to antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Mutant forms of the porin Por result in reduced permeability to antibiotics.

cvterm.name: ole glycosyltransferase
cvterm.definition: OleI and OleD are glycosyltransferases found in Streptomyces antibioticus which is a natural producer of antibiotic oleandomycin. OleI glycosylates antibiotic oleandomycin whereas OleD can glycosylate a wide variety of macrolides.

cvterm.name: dalbavancin
cvterm.definition: Dalbavancin is a semisynthetic second-generation lipoglycopeptide derived from teicoplanin. It binds to the D-Ala-D-Ala terminus of peptidoglycan precursors. It is used to treat Gram-positive bacteria and can be used to treat methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus and vancomycin-resistant enterococci.

cvterm.name: NDM-5
cvterm.definition: New Delhi beta-lactamase NDM-5.

cvterm.name: ethambutol resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genes conferring resistance to ethambutol.

cvterm.name: hydroxypropylphosphonic acid epoxidase
cvterm.definition: The enzyme responsible for the final step of fosfomycin biosynthesis. It converts S-2-hydroxypropylphosphonic acid (S-HPP) into fosfomycin via an oxidative cyclalization reaction. It uses Iron (II) or Zinc (II) as cofactors.

cvterm.name: tetracycline resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genes conferring resistance to tetracycline antibiotics.

cvterm.name: tet31
cvterm.definition: Tet31 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Aeromonas salmonicida, a Gram-negative bacteria. It has also been shown to be expressed in Gallibacterium anatis.

cvterm.name: aminocoumarin resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Point mutations to DNA gyrase subunit B (gyrB) can result in resistance to aminocoumarins. In some cases, expression of parY(R), which encodes an aminocoumarin resistant topoisomerase IV, can also confer aminocoumarin resistance.

cvterm.name: tet33
cvterm.definition: Tet33 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Gram-positive bacteria, including Arthrobacter and Corynebacterium.

cvterm.name: aminocoumarin resistant gyrB
cvterm.definition: Point mutations in DNA gyrase subunit B (gyrB) can result in resistance to aminocoumarins.

cvterm.name: aminocoumarin resistant parY
cvterm.definition: Expression of parY(R), which encodes an aminocoumarin resistant topoisomerase IV, can confer aminocoumarin resistance.

cvterm.name: tet35
cvterm.definition: Tet35 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in the Gram-negative Vibrio and Stenotrophomonas. It is unrelated to other tet resistance genes.

cvterm.name: telavancin
cvterm.definition: Telavancin is a semi-synthetic derivative of vancomycin and is a second-generation lipoglycopeptide antibiotic. Telavancin inhibits cell wall synthesis by forming a complex with the D-Ala-D-Ala terminus of peptidoglycan precursors and preventing transglycosylation.

cvterm.name: sav1866
cvterm.definition: Sav1866 is a multidrug efflux pump in the Gram-positive Staphylococcus aureus. It is a homolog of the human ABC transporter Mdr1 and pumps out toxic compounds including verapamil, tetraphenylphosphorchloride, and Hoechst 33342.

cvterm.name: tuberactinomycin
cvterm.definition: Tuberactinomycins are a family of cyclic peptide antibiotics that are important in the treatment of tuberculosis. Tuberactinomycins contain nonproteinogenic amino acids and inhibit group I self-splicing RNA to disrupt prokaryotic protein synthesis.

cvterm.name: acrD
cvterm.definition: AcrD is an aminoglycoside efflux pump expressed in E. coli. Its expression can be induced by indole, and is regulated by baeRS and cpxAR.

cvterm.name: gene involved in self resistance to antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Definition needed.

cvterm.name: mutant porin OmpF with reduced permeability to antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Mutant forms of the porin OmpF result in reduced permeability to antibiotics.

cvterm.name: glycopeptide resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genes conferring resistance to glycopeptides.

cvterm.name: ErmD
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: vanXYc
cvterm.definition: VanXYc is a protein with both D,D-carboxypeptidase and D,D-dipeptidase activity, found in Enterococcus gallinarum. It cleaves and removes the terminal D-Ala of peptidoglycan subunits for the incorporation of D-Ser by VanC. D-Ala-D-Ser has low binding affinity with vancomycin.

cvterm.name: ethambutol
cvterm.definition: Ethambutol is an antimycobacterial drug prescribed to treat tuberculosis. It is usually given in combination with other tuberculosis drugs, such as isoniazid, rifampicin, and pyrazinamide. Ethambutol inhibits arabinosyl biosynthesis, disrupting mycobacterial cell wall formation.

cvterm.name: ErmF
cvterm.definition: ErmF confers the MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: acrE
cvterm.definition: AcrE is a membrane fusion protein, similar to AcrA.

cvterm.name: phosphonoacetaldehyde methyltransfererase
cvterm.definition: The enzyme responsible for converting phosphonoacetaldehyde to (S)-2-nhydroxypropylphosphonic acid (S-HPP) via an anionic methyl attack, which also reduces the aldehyde to an alcohol.

cvterm.name: Nocardia rifampin resistant beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB2)
cvterm.definition: Due to gene duplication, the genomes of Nocardia species include both rifampin-sensitive beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB) and rifampin-resistant beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB2) genes, with ~88% similarity between the two gene products. Expression of the rpoB2 variant results in replacement of rifampin sensitivity with rifampin resistance.

cvterm.name: acrF
cvterm.definition: AcrF is a inner membrane transporter, similar to AcrB.

cvterm.name: AcrEF-TolC
cvterm.definition: AcrEF-TolC is a tripartite multidrug efflux system similar to AcrAB-TolC and found in Gram-negative bacteria. AcrE is the membrane fusion protein, AcrF is the inner membrane transporter, and TolC is the outer membrane channel protein.

cvterm.name: golS
cvterm.definition: GolS is a regulator activated by the presence of gold, and promotes the expression of the MdsABC efflux pump.

cvterm.name: AR peptide
cvterm.definition: An AR peptide is a peptide sequence predicted to be unique to antibiotic resistance proteins under mass spectrometry analysis. Peptide sequences are predicted from in silico trypsin digestion (cleaves C-terminal side of K or R but not if P is C-terminal to K or R; cysteines treated with nothing). Fragments found in both resistance and non-resistance proteins are not tagged as AR peptides. The reference non-resistance protein set is generated from all complete genome and plasmid sequences in CARD. The completeness of this reference in CARD is important for interpretation of AR peptide tagging. Fragments of less than 6 amino acids are not included.

cvterm.name: mexR
cvterm.definition: MexR is the repressor of the MexRAB-OprM operon. Mutant forms of mexR result in up-regulation of efflux protein MexAB-OprM.

cvterm.name: rifampin resistance RNA polymerase-binding protein
cvterm.definition: Proteins which bind RNA-polymerase and have been experimentally shown to protect RNA-polymerase from rifampin inhibition.

cvterm.name: gadX
cvterm.definition: GadX is an AraC-family regulator that promotes mdtEF expression to confer multidrug resistance.

cvterm.name: mupirocin resistant mupB
cvterm.definition: An alternative isoleucyl-tRNA synthetase conferring resistance to mupirocin.

cvterm.name: evgSA
cvterm.definition: EvgSA is a two-component regulatory system that regulates MdtEF and EmrKY expression for multidrug resistance. EvgS is a sensor protein that phosphorylates the regulatory protein EvgA, though EvgA can be phosphorylated by other methods when it is overexpressed.

cvterm.name: emrR
cvterm.definition: EmrR is a negative regulator for the ErmAB-TolC multidrug efflux pump in E. coli. Mutations lead to ErmAB-TolC overexpression.

cvterm.name: rifaximin
cvterm.definition: Rifaximin is a semi-synthetic rifamycin used to treat traveller's diarrhea. Rifaximin inhibits RNA synthesis by binding to the beta subunit of bacterial RNA polymerase.

cvterm.name: CRP
cvterm.definition: CRP is a global regulator that represses MdtEF multidrug efflux pump expression.

cvterm.name: antibiotic target modifying enzyme
cvterm.definition: Enzymes that confer resistance by modifying antibiotic targets.

cvterm.name: isoniazid
cvterm.definition: Isoniazid is an organic compound that is the first-line anti tuberculosis medication in prevention and treatment. As a prodrug, it is activated by mycobacterial catalase-peroxidases such as M. tuberculosis KatG. Isoniazid inhibits mycolic acid synthesis, which prevents cell wall synthesis in mycobacteria.

cvterm.name: mupirocin resistant mupA
cvterm.definition: An alternative isoleucyl-tRNA synthetase conferring resistance to mupirocin.

cvterm.name: ErmG
cvterm.definition: ErmG is a rRNA adenine N-6-methyltransferase that protects the ribosome from inactivation due to antibiotic binding.

cvterm.name: cpxAR
cvterm.definition: CpxAR is a two-component regulatory system that involves a sensor kinase, CpxA, and the regulator CpxR. When the membrane envelope is stressed, CpxAR promotes acrD and mdtABC expression to confer multidrug resistance through efflux.

cvterm.name: antibiotic A40926
cvterm.definition: A40926 is a glycopeptide antibiotic produced by Nonomuraea sp. ATCC 39727. It is precusor of the second-generation glycopeptide antibiotic dalbavancin.

cvterm.name: cmeR
cvterm.definition: CmeR is a repressor for the CmeABC multidrug efflux pump, binding to the cmeABC promoter region.

cvterm.name: polyamine antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Polyamine antibiotics are organic compounds having two or more primary amino groups.

cvterm.name: chlortetracycline
cvterm.definition: Chlortetracycline was an early, first-generation tetracycline antibiotic developed in the 1940's. It inhibits bacterial protein synthesis by binding to the 30S subunit of bacterial ribosomes, preventing the aminoacyl-tRNA from binding to the ribosome.

cvterm.name: mupirocin resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genes conferring resistance to the antibiotic mupirocin.

cvterm.name: rifabutin
cvterm.definition: Rifabutin is a semisynthetic rifamycin used in tuberculosis therapy. It inhibits DNA-dependent RNA synthesis.

cvterm.name: baeSR
cvterm.definition: BaeSR is a two component regulatory system for efflux proteins in Gram-negative bacteria. BaeR is a response regulator, while BaeS is a sensor kinase.

cvterm.name: aminocoumarin biosynthesis
cvterm.definition: Biosynthesis of aminocoumarin antibiotics.

cvterm.name: macA
cvterm.definition: MacA is a membrane fusion protein that forms an antibiotic efflux complex with MacB and TolC.

cvterm.name: rifapentine
cvterm.definition: Rifapentine is a semisynthetic rifamycin that inhibits DNA-dependent RNA synthesis. It is often used in the treatment of tuberculosis and leprosy.

cvterm.name: macB
cvterm.definition: MacB is an ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporter that exports macrolides with 14- or 15- membered lactones. It forms an antibiotic efflux complex with MacA and TolC.

cvterm.name: Streptomyces spheroides novobiocin biosynthetic gene cluster
cvterm.definition: Novobiocin is produced from biosynthetic clusters in Streptomyces spheroides and Streptomyces niveus.

cvterm.name: MacAB-TolC
cvterm.definition: MacAB-TolC is an ABC efflux pump complex expressed in E. coli and Salmonella enterica. It confers resistance to macrolides, including erythromycin.

cvterm.name: Streptomyces roseochromogenes subsp. oscitans clorobiocin biosynthetic gene cluster
cvterm.definition: Clorobiocin is produced by a biosynthetic cluster in Streptomyces roseochromogenes.

cvterm.name: arlRS
cvterm.definition: ArlRS is a two-component regulatory system for NorA. ArlS phosphorylates ArlR to promote NorA expression.

cvterm.name: Streptomyces rishiriensis strain DSM 40489 coumermycin A1 biosynthetic gene cluster
cvterm.definition: Coumermycin A1 is produced by a biosynthetic cluster in Streptomyces rishiriensis.

cvterm.name: adeS
cvterm.definition: AdeS is a sensor kinase in the AdeRS regulatory system of AdeABC. It is essential for AdeABC expression.

cvterm.name: aztreonam
cvterm.definition: Aztreonam was the first monobactam discovered, and is greatly effective against Gram-negative bacteria while inactive against Gram-positive bacteria. Artreonam is a poor substrate for beta-lactamases, and may even act as an inhibitor. In Gram-negative bacteria, Aztreonam interferes with filamentation, inhibiting cell division and leading to cell death.

cvterm.name: organoarsenic antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Organoarsenic antibiotics are arsenic-containing compounds with antibacterial effects. The organoarsenic antibiotic arsphenamine and its derivatives were developed in the 1910s as the first modern chemotherapeutic agents.

cvterm.name: arsphenamine
cvterm.definition: Arsphenamine, also known as Salvarsan and 606, is a drug that was used beginning in the 1910s to treat syphilis and trypanosomiasis. It is an organoarsenic compound and was the first modern chemotherapeutic agent.

cvterm.name: adeR
cvterm.definition: AdeR is a positive regulator of AdeABC efflux system. AdeR inactivation leads to susceptibility to aminoglycoside antibiotics.

cvterm.name: mupirocin
cvterm.definition: Mupirocin, also known as pseudomonic acid, is a bacteriostatic polyketide antibiotic from Pseudomonas fluorescens used to treat S. aureus and MRSA. It inhibits Ile tRNA synthetase.

cvterm.name: macrolide biosynthesis
cvterm.definition: Biosynthesis of macrolide antibiotics.

cvterm.name: tet44
cvterm.definition: Tet44 is a tetracycline resistance gene found in Campylobacter fetus, and binds to the ribosome to confer antibiotic resistance as a ribosomal protection protein.

cvterm.name: antibiotic inactivation enzyme
cvterm.definition: Enzyme that catalyzes the inactivation of an antibiotic resulting in resistance. Inactivation includes chemical modification, destruction, etc.

cvterm.name: sulfonamide resistant dihydropteroate synthase
cvterm.definition: Folate is an essential precursor for many nucleotides and amino acids, making folate biosynthesis a desirable target for antibiotics. Mutation to enzymes within the folate biosynthetic pathway can reverse antibiotic action. Modification of dihydropteroate synthase (folP) can result in resistance to sulfonamide antibiotics. Resistance can be conferred by mutation to the native folP gene or by acquiring a resistant DHPS (sul) gene through gene transfer. The sul gene has three known variants (sul1, sul2, sul3) and encodes a highly resistant dihydropteroate synthase that can be acquired via transposons or plasmids.

cvterm.name: adeN
cvterm.definition: AdeN is a repressor of AdeIJK, a RND-type efflux pump in Acinetobacter baumannii. Its inactivation increases expression of AdeJ.

cvterm.name: Erm 23S ribosomal RNA methyltransferase
cvterm.definition: Erm proteins are part of the RNA methyltransferase family and methylate A2058 (E. coli nomenclature) of the 23S ribosomal RNA conferring degrees of resistance to Macrolides, Lincosamides and Streptogramin b. This is called the MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: tet30
cvterm.definition: Tet30 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in agrobacterium, a Gram-negative bacterium.

cvterm.name: tet38
cvterm.definition: Tet38 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in the Gram-positive Staphylococcus aureus. It is regulated by mgrA, which also regulates NorB.

cvterm.name: tet39
cvterm.definition: Tet39 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Gram-negative bacteria, including Brevundimonas, Stenotrophomonas, Enterobacter, Alcaligenes, Acinetobacter, and Providencia.

cvterm.name: tet40
cvterm.definition: Tet40 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in the Gram-positive Clostridium. It is similar to tetA(P).

cvterm.name: subclass B1 (metallo-) beta-lactamase
cvterm.definition: Subclass B1 possess a binuclear active site. Within this active site can be either one or two Zn(II) ions. This subclass is able to hydrolyze penicillins, cephalosporins and carbapenems. This is the most clinically relevant subclass of MBLs.

cvterm.name: tet41
cvterm.definition: Tet41 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Serratia, a Gram-negative bacterium. It is related to Acinetobacter Tet(39).

cvterm.name: subclass B2 (metallo-) beta-lactamase
cvterm.definition: Metallo-beta-lactmases of subclass B2 contain only one Zn ion in their active site and selectively hydrolyze carbapenems.

cvterm.name: subclass B3 (metallo-) beta-lactamase
cvterm.definition: Metallo-beta-lactamases of subclass B3 are similar to B1 in that they have activity against penicillins, cephalosporins and carbapenems; however, the are only active with two Zn(II) ions in the active site.

cvterm.name: tet42
cvterm.definition: Tet42 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in both Gram-negative (Pseudomonas) and Gram-positive (Microbacterium, Bacillus, Staphylococcus, Paenibacillus) bacteria.

cvterm.name: tet43
cvterm.definition: Tet(43) is a tetracycline resistance gene with unknown origins, isolated from metagenomic DNA.

cvterm.name: vanR
cvterm.definition: VanR is a OmpR-family transcriptional activator in the VanSR regulatory system. When activated by VanS, it promotes cotranscription of VanA, VanH, and VanX.

cvterm.name: vanU
cvterm.definition: VanU is a transcriptional activator of the vanG operon of vancomycin resistance genes.

cvterm.name: rifampin inactivation enzyme
cvterm.definition: Enzymes that inactivate rifampin antibiotics by chemical modification.

cvterm.name: BcII beta-lactamase
cvterm.definition: Bacillus cereus beta-lactamase II (BcII)

cvterm.name: CcrA beta-lactamase
cvterm.definition: CcrA beta-lactamases, usually found in Bacteroides fragilis, hydrolyse most beta-lactams.

cvterm.name: BlaB beta-lactamase
cvterm.definition: Beta-lactamase B (BlaB) mediates resistance against many beta-lactam antibiotics, notably penams and carbapenems.

cvterm.name: SPM beta-lactamase
cvterm.definition: Sao Paulo metallo-beta-lactamase (SPM-1)

cvterm.name: CphA beta-lactamase
cvterm.definition: CphA is an Ambler Class B MBL; subclass B2 originally isolated from Aeromonas hydrophilia. This enzyme has specific activity against carbapenems and is active as a mono-zinc protein.

cvterm.name: L1 beta-lactamase
cvterm.definition: L1 is an Ambler class B MBL; subclass B3 originally isolated from Stenotrophomonas maltophilia. It has activity against a broad range of beta-lactams and is only active with two Zn(II) ions in the active site.

cvterm.name: pristinamycin IA
cvterm.definition: Pristinamycin 1A is a type B streptogramin antibiotic produced by Streptomyces pristinaespiralis. It binds to the P site of the 50S subunit of the bacterial ribosome, preventing the extension of protein chains.

cvterm.name: quinupristin
cvterm.definition: Quinupristin is a type B streptogramin and a semisynthetic derivative of pristinamycin 1A. It is a component of the drug Synercid and interacts with the 50S subunit of the bacterial ribosome to inhibit protein synthesis.

cvterm.name: pulvomycin
cvterm.definition: Pulvomycin is a polyketide antibiotic that binds elongation factor Tu (EF-Tu) to inhibit protein biosynthesis. It is not clinically used.

cvterm.name: sulbactam
cvterm.definition: inhibitor of non-AmpC Ser beta-lactmases

cvterm.name: avibactam
cvterm.definition: Ser beta-lactamase inhibitor targeting class A and class C enzymes

cvterm.name: NDM-1
cvterm.definition: NDM-1 is a metallo-beta-lactamase discovered from a Swedish patient carrying a Klebsiella pneumoniae infection after hospitalization in India.

cvterm.name: NDM-2
cvterm.definition: NDM-2 was isolated from a strain of Acinetobacter baumannii in Germany from a patient hospitalized in Cairo. A single amino acid substitution (P28R) differentiates this gene from NDM-1 and the two enzymes appear to have an identical spectrum of hydrolysis.

cvterm.name: ErmI
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: ErmN
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: ErmQ
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: ErmR
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: ErmT
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: ErmX
cvterm.definition: ErmX is a rRNA methyltransferase that protects the ribosome from inactivation due to antibiotic binding.

cvterm.name: ErmZ
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: Erm(31)
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: Erm(33)
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: Erm(34)
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: Erm(38)
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: Erm(39)
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: Erm(41)
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.

cvterm.name: Erm(35)
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.n

cvterm.name: Erm(36)
cvterm.definition: ErmD confers MLSb phenotype.n

cvterm.name: FEZ-1 beta-lactamase
cvterm.definition: FEZ-1 is an Ambler class B MBL; subclass B3 first isolated from Legionella gormanii. It has activity against a broad range of beta-lactams and is only active with two Zn(II) ions in the active site.

cvterm.name: gene detected by antibiotic resistance screening microarray
cvterm.definition: Many genes involved in antibiotic resistance are mobile and microarray probes for these genes can thus provide positive results for any number of organisms. CARD stores the coding sequences of genes targeted by the probe sets of available antibiotic resistance microarrays.

cvterm.name: macrolide resistance efflux pump
cvterm.definition: Mel and Mef efflux pumps are responsible for macrolide resistance in Streptococcus pneumoniae.

cvterm.name: mefE
cvterm.definition: mefE is one of two proton motive efflux pumps in Streptococcus pneumoniae that confers resistance to macrolides. It is found on the same operon as mefA and the ABC-efflux pump mel.

cvterm.name: mefA
cvterm.definition: mefA is one of two proton motive efflux pumps in Streptococcus pneumoniae that confers resistance to macrolides. It is found on the same operon as mefE and the ABC-efflux pump mel.

cvterm.name: mel
cvterm.definition: Mel, a homolog of MsrA, is an ABC transporter associated with macrolide resistance. It is expressed on the same operon as mefA and mefE, both MFS-type efflux proteins that confer macrolide resistance.

cvterm.name: mecA (methicillin resistant PBP2)
cvterm.definition: In methicillin sensitive S. aureus (MSSA), beta-lactams bind to native penicillin-binding proteins (PBPs) and disrupt synthesis of the cell membrane's peptidoglycan layer. In methicillin resistant S. aureus (MRSA), foreign PBP2a (encoded by mecA) acquired by lateral gene transfer is able to perform peptidoglycan synthesis in the presence of beta-lactams.

cvterm.name: fluoroquinolone resistant gyrA
cvterm.definition: DNA gyrase is responsible for DNA supercoiling and consists of two alpha and two beta subunits. GyrA point mutations confer resistance by preventing fluoroquinolone antibiotics from binding the alpha-subunit. Mutations at sites G81 and D87 are observed in Mycobacterium tuberculosis.

cvterm.name: fluoroquinolone resistant parC
cvterm.definition: ParC is a subunit of topoisomerase IV, which decatenates and relaxes DNA to allow access to genes for transcription or translation. Point mutations in ParC prevent fluoroquinolone antibiotics from inhibiting DNA synthesis, and confer low-level resistance. Higher-level resistance results from both gyrA and parC mutations.

cvterm.name: adeL
cvterm.definition: AdeL is a regulator of AdeFGH in Acinetobacter baumannii. AdeL mutations are associated with AdeFGH overexpression and multidrug resistance.

cvterm.name: PC1 beta-lactamase (blaZ)
cvterm.definition: blaZ beta-lactamases.

cvterm.name: colistin A
cvterm.definition: Colistin A, or polymyxin E1, has a 6-octanoic acid lipid tail. Polymyxins disrupt the cell membrane of Gram-negative bacteria.

cvterm.name: colistin B
cvterm.definition: Colistin B, or polymyxin E2, has a 6-heptanoic acid lipid tail. Polymyxins disrupt the cell membrane of Gram-negative bacteria.

cvterm.name: polymyxin B1
cvterm.definition: Polymyxin B1 is in the family of polymyxin lipopeptides with a 6-methyloctanoic acid acyl group. These antibiotics disrupt the cell membrane of Gram-negative bacteria.

cvterm.name: polymyxin B2
cvterm.definition: Polymyxin B2 is in the family of polymyxin lipopeptides with a 6-methylheptanoic acid acyl group. These antibiotics disrupt the cell membrane of Gram-negative bacteria.

cvterm.name: polymyxin B3
cvterm.definition: Polymyxin B3 is in the family of polymyxin lipopeptides with an octanoic acid acyl group. These antibiotics disrupt the cell membrane of Gram-negative bacteria.

cvterm.name: polymyxin B4
cvterm.definition: Polymyxin B4 is in the family of polymyxin lipopeptides with a heptanoic acid acyl group. These antibiotics disrupt the cell membrane of Gram-negative bacteria.

cvterm.name: bacitracin A
cvterm.definition: Bacitracin A is the primary component of bacitracin. It contains many uncommon amino acids and interferes with bacterial cell wall synthesis.

cvterm.name: bacitracin B
cvterm.definition: Bacitracin B is a component of bacitracin, an antibiotic mixture that interferes with bacterial cell wall synthesis. It differs from Bacitracin A with a valine instead of an isoleucine in its peptide.

cvterm.name: bacitracin F
cvterm.definition: Bacitracin F is a component of bacitracin, an antibiotic mixture that interferes with bacterial cell wall synthesis. It is formed when the thiazoline ring of bacitracin A is oxidatively deaminated.

cvterm.name: benzylpenicillin
cvterm.definition: Benzylpenicillin, commonly referred to as penicillin G, is effective against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria. It is unstable in acid.

cvterm.name: phenoxymethylpenicillin
cvterm.definition: Phenoxymethylpenicillin, or penicillin V, is a penicillin derivative that is acid stable but less active than benzylpenicillin (penicillin G).

cvterm.name: propicillin
cvterm.definition: Propicillin is an orally taken penicillin derivative that has high absorption but poor activity.

cvterm.name: dicloxacillin
cvterm.definition: Dicloxacillin is a penicillin derivative that has an extra chlorine atom in comparison to cloxacillin. While more active than cloxacillin, its high affinity for serum protein reduces its activity in human serum in vitro.

cvterm.name: flucloxacillin
cvterm.definition: Flucloxacillin is similar to cloxacillin, with an extra additional fluorine atom.

cvterm.name: ampicillin
cvterm.definition: Ampicillin is a penicillin derivative that is highly acid stable, with its activity similar to benzylpenicillin.

cvterm.name: azlocillin
cvterm.definition: Azlocillin is a semisynthetic derivative of penicillin that is notably active against Ps. aeruginosa and other Gram-negative bacteria.

cvterm.name: mezlocillin
cvterm.definition: Mezlocillin is a penicillin derivative taken parenterally.

cvterm.name: doripenem
cvterm.definition: Doripenem is a carbapenem with a broad range of activity against Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, and along with meropenem, it is the most active beta-lactam antibiotic against Pseudomonas aeruginosa. It inhibits bacterial cell wall synthesis.

cvterm.name: cefalexin
cvterm.definition: Cefalexin is a cephalosporin antibiotic that causes filamentation. It is resistant to staphylococcal beta-lactamase, but degraded by enterobacterial beta-lactamases.

cvterm.name: cefadroxil
cvterm.definition: Cefadroxil, or p-hydroxycephalexin, is an cephalosporin antibiotic similar to cefalexin.

cvterm.name: cefotiam
cvterm.definition: Cefotiam is a cephalosporin antibiotic with similar activity to cefuroxime but more active against enterobacteria. It is consumed orally as the prodrug cefotiam hexetil.

cvterm.name: cefaclor
cvterm.definition: Cefaclor is a semisynthetic cephalosporin derived from cephalexin. It has broad-spectrum antibiotic activity.

cvterm.name: cefotaxime
cvterm.definition: Cefotaxime is a semisynthetic cephalosporin taken parenterally. It is resistant to most beta-lactamases and active against Gram-negative rods and cocci due to its aminothiazoyl and methoximino functional groups.

cvterm.name: cefixime
cvterm.definition: Cefixime is a cephalosporin resistant to most beta-lactamases. It is active against many enterobacteria, but activity against staphylococci is poor.

cvterm.name: cefpodoxime
cvterm.definition: Cefpodoxime is a semisynthetic cephalosporin that acts similarly to cefotaxime with broad-spectrum activity. It is stable to many plasmid-mediated beta-lactamses. Cefpodoxime is consumed as the prodrug cefpodoxime proxetil.

cvterm.name: ceftibuten
cvterm.definition: Ceftibuten is a semisynthetic cephalosporin active against Gram-negative bacilli. It is resistant against many plasmid-mediated beta-lactamases.

cvterm.name: cefditoren
cvterm.definition: Cefditoren is a semisynthetic cephalosporin active against staphylococci, streptococci, and and most enterobacteria. It is resistant to staphylococcal and most enterobacterial beta-lactamases, and is usually taken as the prodrug cefditoren pivoxil.

cvterm.name: cefdinir
cvterm.definition: Cefdinir is similar to cefixime with a modified side-chain at its 7-amino position. It also shares similar activity with cefixime but is more active against staphylococci. It has also be shown to enhance phagocytosis.

cvterm.name: ceftaroline
cvterm.definition: Ceftaroline is a novel cephalosporin active against methicillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus. Like other cephalosporins it binds penicillin-binding proteins to inhibit cell wall synthesis. It strongly binds with PBP2a, associated with methicillin resistance. It is taken orally as the prodrug ceftaroline fosamil.

cvterm.name: isepamicin
cvterm.definition: A semi-synthetic derivative of gentamicin B (hydroxyamino propionyl genamicin B). It is modified to combat microbial inactivation and has a slightly larger spectrum of activity compared to other aminoglycosides, including Ser marcescens, Enterobacteria, and K pneumoniae.

cvterm.name: G418
cvterm.definition: A gentamicin class aminoglycoside antibiotic often used in mammalian cell culture work as a selectable marker for the neo cassette (APH3').

cvterm.name: arbekacin
cvterm.definition: A synthetic derivative (1-N-(4-amino-2-hydroxybutyryl) of dibekacin used in Japan. It is active against methicillin-resistant Staph. aureus and shows synergy with ampicillin when treating gentamicin and vancomycin resistant enterocci.

cvterm.name: gentamicin B
cvterm.definition: Gentamicin B is a semisynthetic aminoglycoside antibacterial.

cvterm.name: acrS
cvterm.definition: AcrS is a repressor of the AcrAB efflux complex and is associated with the expression of AcrEF. AcrS is believed to regulate a switch between AcrAB and AcrEF efflux.

cvterm.name: paromomycin
cvterm.definition: An aminoglycoside antibiotic used for the treatment of parasitic infections. It is similar to neomycin sharing a similar spectrum of activity, but its hydroxyl group at the 6'-position instead of an amino group makes it resistant to AAC(6') modifying enzymes.

cvterm.name: lividomycin
cvterm.definition: Lividomycins are aminoglycosidic antibiotics produced by Streptomyces lividus. They contain 2-amino-2,3-dideoxy-D-glucose.

cvterm.name: gatifloxacin
cvterm.definition: Gatifloxacin is an 8-methoxy, 7-piperazinyl, 6-fluoroquinolone that can be taken orally or by intravenous administration. It is active against most Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, but inactive against non-fermenting Gram-negative rods including Pseudomonas aeruginosa.

cvterm.name: lomefloxacin
cvterm.definition: Lomefloxacin is a difluoropiperazinyl quinolone, sharing similar activities with other fluoroquinolones. It is used to treat urinary tract infections. Relative to other fluoroquinolones, it has a longer half life and has higher serum concentrations.

cvterm.name: nalidixic acid
cvterm.definition: Nalidixic acid is a quinolone derivative of naphthyridine active against many enterobacteria, but ineffective against Ps aeruginosa, Gram-positive bacteria, and anaerobes. Acquired resistance is common in nalidixic acid treatments.

cvterm.name: norfloxacin
cvterm.definition: Norfloxacin is a 6-fluoro, 7-piperazinyl quinolone with a wide range of activity against Gram-negative bacteria. It is inactive against most anaerobes.

cvterm.name: ofloxacin
cvterm.definition: Ofloxacin is a 6-fluoro, 7-piperazinyl quinolone with a methyl-substituted oxazine ring. It has a broad spectrum of activity including many enterobacteria and mycoplasma but most anaerobes are resistant.

cvterm.name: trovafloxacin
cvterm.definition: Trovafloxacin is a trifluoroquinalone with a broad spectrum of activity that acts by inhibiting the uncoiling of supercoiled DNA. While potent against many Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, it is less active against pseudomonads and Cl. difficile. It is usually taken as the prodrug trovafloxacin mesylate or alatrofloxacin mesylate for oral or intravenous administration, respectively.

cvterm.name: grepafloxacin
cvterm.definition: Grepafloxacin is a broad-spectrum antibacterial quinoline. It is no longer taken due to its high toxicity.

cvterm.name: sparfloxacin
cvterm.definition: Sparfloxacin is a dimethylpiperazinyl difluoroquinolone that acts by inhibiting DNA gyrase. It is active against aerobic Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, as well as some mycobacteria. It has moderate activity against some anaerobes.

cvterm.name: demeclocycline
cvterm.definition: Demeclocycline is a tetracycline analog with 7-chloro and 6-methyl groups. Due to its fast absorption and slow excretion, it maintains higher effective blood levels compared to other tetracyclines.

cvterm.name: oxytetracycline
cvterm.definition: Oxytetracycline is a derivative of tetracycline with a 5-hydroxyl group. Its activity is similar to other tetracyclines.

cvterm.name: pristinamycin IIA
cvterm.definition: Pristinamycin IIA is a streptogramin A antibiotic.

cvterm.name: pleuromutilin
cvterm.definition: Pleuromutilins are natural fungal products that target bacterial protein translation by binding the the 23S rRNA, blocking the ribosome P site at the 50S subunit. They are mostly used for agriculture and veterinary purposes.

cvterm.name: tiamulin
cvterm.definition: Tiamulin is a pleuromutilin derivative currently used in veterinary medicine. It binds to the 23 rRNA of the 50S ribosomal subunit to inhibit protein translation.

cvterm.name: madumycin II
cvterm.definition: Madumycin II is a streptogramin A antibiotic.

cvterm.name: griseoviridin
cvterm.definition: Griseoviridin is a streptogramin A antibiotic.

cvterm.name: dalfopristin
cvterm.definition: Dalfopristin is a water-soluble semi-synthetic derivative of pristinamycin IIA. It is produced by Streptomyces pristinaespiralis and is used in combination with quinupristin in a 7:3 ratio. Both work together to inhibit protein synthesis, and is active against Gram-positive bacteria.

cvterm.name: pristinamycin IB
cvterm.definition: Pristinamycin IB is a class B streptogramin similar to pristinamycin IA, the former containing a N-methyl-4-(methylamino)phenylalanine instead of a N-methyl-4-(dimethylamino)phenylalanine in its class A streptogramin counterpart (one less methyl group).

cvterm.name: H-NS
cvterm.definition: H-NS is a histone-like protein involved in global gene regulation in Gram-negative bacteria. It is a repressor of the membrane fusion protein genes acrE, mdtE, and emrK as well as nearby genes of many RND-type multidrug exporters.

cvterm.name: virginiamycin S2
cvterm.definition: Virginiamycin S2 is a streptogramin B antibiotic.

cvterm.name: vernamycin B-gamma
cvterm.definition: Vernamycin B-gamma is a class B streptogramin derived from virginiamycin S1.

cvterm.name: vernamycin C
cvterm.definition: Vernamycin C is a streptogramin B antibiotic.

cvterm.name: patricin A
cvterm.definition: Patricin A is a streptogramin B antibiotic.

cvterm.name: patricin B
cvterm.definition: Patricin B is a streptogramin B antibiotic.

cvterm.name: ostreogrycin B3
cvterm.definition: Ostreogrycin B3 is a derivative of pristinamycin IA, with an additional 3-hydroxy group on its 4-oxopipecolic acid.

cvterm.name: sulfacetamide
cvterm.definition: Sulfacetamide is a very soluable sulfonamide antibiotic previously used to treat urinary tract infections. Its relatively low activity and toxicity to those with Stevens-Johnson syndrome have reduced its use and availability.

cvterm.name: mafenide
cvterm.definition: Mafenide is a sulfonamide used topically for treating burns.

cvterm.name: arylomycin
cvterm.definition: Arylomycins are lipopeptide antibiotics, sharing a lipohexapeptide with a C-terminal tripeptide macrolide and varying by the length of its alkyl chains.

cvterm.name: thiostrepton
cvterm.definition: Thiostrepton is a cyclic peptide active against Gram-positive bacteria. It is produced by streptomyces bacteria.

cvterm.name: moenomycin
cvterm.definition: Moemomycin antibiotics are phosphoglycolipids that contain a 3-phosphoglyceric acid, often used as a mixture. They inhibit petidoglycan glycosyltransferases to prevent bacterial cell wall biosynthesis.

cvterm.name: furazolidone
cvterm.definition: Furazolidone is a nitrofuran antibiotic that is a non-ionic synthetic compound. It is taken orally and is active against many enteric pathogens. Furazolidone also has antiprotozoal activity and acts by inhibiting monoamine oxidase.

cvterm.name: metronidazole
cvterm.definition: Metronidazole is a nitroimidazole that is active against anaerobic bacteria and protozoa. It is not effective against aerobic bacteria. Nitroimidazoles act by oxidizing DNA causing strand breaks and cell death.

cvterm.name: bleomycinic acid
cvterm.definition: Bleomycinic acid is a glycopeptide antibiotic produced by Streptomyces verticillus taken as a mixture of bleomycins. It induces stand breaks in bacterial nucleic acids.

cvterm.name: bleomycin A2
cvterm.definition: Bleomycin A2 is a glycopeptide antibiotic produced by Streptomyces verticillus taken as a mixture of bleomycins. It induces stand breaks in bacterial nucleic acids.

cvterm.name: bleomycin B2
cvterm.definition: Bleomycin B2 is a glycopeptide antibiotic produced by Streptomyces verticillus taken as a mixture of bleomycins. It induces stand breaks in bacterial nucleic acids.

cvterm.name: defensin
cvterm.definition: Defensins are natural cationic peptides that have antibiotic properties. It is part of the innate immune system of plants and animals.

cvterm.name: magainin
cvterm.definition: Magainins are antimicrobial peptides produced by amphibians as part of their innate immune system.

cvterm.name: actinomycin
cvterm.definition: Actinomycins are peptide antibiotics that interact with DNA. This prevents RNA synthesis, thus preventing the production of proteins vital to the cell.

cvterm.name: actinomycin D
cvterm.definition: Actinomycin D is a cyclic peptide antibiotic that interacts with DNA to inhibit RNA synthesis.

cvterm.name: moenomycin A1
cvterm.definition: Moenomycin A1 is a major component of moenomycin mixtures. It is produced by Streptomyces ghanaensis, S. bambergiensis, S. ederensis, and S. geysiriensis.

cvterm.name: sulfasalazine
cvterm.definition: Sulfasalazine is a derivative of the early sulfonamide sulfapyridine (salicylazosulfapyridine). It was developed to increase water solubility and is taken orally for ulcerative colitis.

cvterm.name: sulfamethizole
cvterm.definition: Sulfamethizole is a short-acting sulfonamide that inhibits dihydropteroate synthetase.

cvterm.name: lividomycin A
cvterm.definition: Lividomycin A is a pentasaccharide antibiotic which interferes with bacterial protein synthesis.

cvterm.name: lividomycin B
cvterm.definition: Lividomycin B is a derivative of lividomycin A with a removed mannose group (demannosyllividomycin A). Livodomycins interfere with bacterial protein synthesis.

cvterm.name: acrR
cvterm.definition: AcrR is a repressor of the AcrAB-TolC multidrug efflux complex. AcrR mutations result in high level antibiotic resistance.

cvterm.name: cefalotin
cvterm.definition: Cefalotin is a semisynthetic cephalosporin antibiotic activate against staphylococci. It is resistant to staphylococci beta-lactamases but hydrolyzed by enterobacterial beta-lactamases.

cvterm.name: isopenicillin N
cvterm.definition: Isopenicillin N is a natural penicillin derivative produced by Penicillium chrysogenum with activity similar to penicillin N.

cvterm.name: penicillin N
cvterm.definition: Penicillin N is a penicillin derivative produced by Cephalosporium acremonium.

cvterm.name: mixture
cvterm.definition: Mixtures of antibiotics are commonly used clinically. These mixtures link to antibiotic molecules that are also listed in their respective families under antibiotic molecules. i.e. 'Gramicidin A' is part of the mixture 'gramicidin D', while 'Gramicidin A' is also a 'gramicidin', which is a 'peptide antibiotic'.

cvterm.name: antibiotic target
cvterm.definition: Antibiotic targets are components of the bacterial cell usually unique to bacteria or significantly different from their eukaryotic counterparts to allow for selective antibacterial activity. Exceptions include antibiotics that are converted to an active form inside the bacterium. Resistance mechanisms may modify these targets to protect bacteria from the effects of antibiotics.

cvterm.name: cell wall synthesis enzyme targeted by antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Cell wall biosynthesis provides bacteria with a layer of peptidoglycan that provides rigidity and protects the cell from lysis due to osmotic pressure. Cell wall structures vary significantly between Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, while mycobacteria have a unique cell wall composition.

cvterm.name: cell membrane component targeted by antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Interaction with the cell membrane phospholipids interferes with membrane permeability and integrity, leading to the leakage of cell contents. The outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria is particularly sensitive.

cvterm.name: protein synthesis machinery targeted by antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Protein synthesis in bacteria is accomplished by cytosolic ribosomes that are structurally different from eukaryotic ribosomes, and thus a target for many antibiotics. By inhibiting ribosomal activity, either by directly binding to the ribosome or interacting with co-factors, antibiotics prevent protein synthesis.

cvterm.name: nucleic acid synthesis machinery targeted by antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Bacterial DNA and RNA synthesis includes many enzymes unique to bacteria that are targeted by antibiotics.

cvterm.name: nucleic acid targeted by antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Nucleic acids can also be targeted by antibiotics. These drugs are usually converted to an active form by enzymes unique to bacteria to prevent toxicity to the host.

cvterm.name: folate synthesis enzyme targeted by antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Enzymes in the folate synthesis pathway are targeted by two main classes of antibiotics: sulfonamides and diaminopyrimidines. Inhibition of these enzymes block the production of key precursors for nucleotides and amino acids.

cvterm.name: isoprenoid synthesis enzyme targeted by antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Enzymes in this pathway generate important precursors for macromolecules. While eukaryotes and prokaryotes both synthesize isoprenoids, many bacteria and notably mycobacteria use an alternative pathway that is targeted by antibiotics.

cvterm.name: mycolic acid synthesis enzyme targeted by antibiotic
cvterm.definition: Mycolic acids are produced by mycobacteria. These fatty acids are required for the construction of cell walls. Enzymes that are targeted by antibiotics include synthases, elongases, and dehydrogenases.

cvterm.name: antibiotic sensitive signal peptidase I
cvterm.definition: Signal peptidase I is a bacterial signal peptidase that cleaves signal peptides from translated proteins. These signal peptides direct proteins to their destination, and then must be cleaved in order to function.

cvterm.name: marR
cvterm.definition: MarR is a repressor of the mar operon marRAB, thus regulating the expression of marA, the activator of multidrug efflux pump AcrAB.

cvterm.name: bacitracin sensitive isoprenyl pyrophosphate
cvterm.definition: Isoprepnyl pyrophosphate removes a phosphate group that is added from the peptidoglycan subunit to permit its transfer across the cell membrane. The phosphate group must be removed before its incorporation into peptidoglycan macromolecules.

cvterm.name: acyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine
cvterm.definition: The acyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine group is found at the terminal end of the pentapeptide chains of peptidoglycan subunits. Antibiotics that bind to this group block the addition of subunits, inhibiting peptidoglycan synthesis. This group is most accessible in Gram-postive bacteria.

cvterm.name: cell wall component targeted by antibiotic
cvterm.definition: The cell wall is unique to bacteria and provides rigidity and protects the cell from lysis due to osmotic pressure. Its characteristic component is peptidoglycan, though cell wall structures vary significantly between Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, as well as mycobacteria.

cvterm.name: cycloserine sensitive alanine racemase
cvterm.definition: Alanine racemase converts the natural L-alanine to the D-alanine required in the pentapeptide chains in peptidoglycan. It is found in both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria.

cvterm.name: cycloserine sensitive D-alanine synthetase
cvterm.definition: D-Alanine synthetase joins two D-alanines before their addition to the pentapeptide chains of peptidoglycan. It is found in both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria.

cvterm.name: fosfomycin sensitive pyruvyl transferase
cvterm.definition: Pyruvyl transferase is responsible for the conversion of N-acetylglucosamine (NAG) to N-acetylmuramic acid (NAMA). NAMA is a part of the macromolecular backbone of peptidoglycans. Pyruvyl transferase is found in both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria.

cvterm.name: ethambutol sensitive arabinosyltransferase (embB)
cvterm.definition: Arabinosyl transferases allow for the polymerization of arabinose to form arabinan. Arabanan is required for formation of mycobacterial cell walls.

cvterm.name: pentaglycyl bridge
cvterm.definition: The pentaglycyl bridge is part of Gram-positive peptidoglycan, allowing the formation of a thick and rigid cell wall.

cvterm.name: 50S ribosomal subunit
cvterm.definition: The larger of two ribosomal subunits that make up the 70S bacterial ribosome.

cvterm.name: 30S ribosomal subunit
cvterm.definition: The smaller of two ribosomal subunits that make up the 70S bacterial ribosome.

cvterm.name: ribosomal complex
cvterm.definition: The ribosomal complex can be targeted by antibiotics that stabilize the entire complex and prevent further translation. These antibiotics target both subunits in the process of protein translation.

cvterm.name: elongation factor G
cvterm.definition: Elongation factor G (EF-G) provides energy for the translocation step in protein synthesis. Antibiotics that target EF-G allow one round of translocation but prevent EF-G from dissociating from the ribosome-RNA complex.

cvterm.name: elongation factor Tu
cvterm.definition: Elongation factor Tu is required for peptide elongation in bacterial protein synthesis.

cvterm.name: mupirocin sensitive isoleucyl-tRNA transferase
cvterm.definition: Isoleucyl-tRNA transferase recognizes isoleucine codons and works with the ribosome to incorporate isoleucine amino acids into polypeptide chains. It can be targeted by antibiotics that have an analog of isoleucine through competitive inhibition.

cvterm.name: fluoroquinolone sensitive gyrA
cvterm.definition: DNA gyrase is responsible for DNA supercoiling and consists of two alpha and two beta subunits. Binding the alpha-subunit is sufficient to inhibit DNA supercoiling.

cvterm.name: antibiotic sensitive gyrB
cvterm.definition: DNA gyrase is responsible for DNA supercoiling and consists of two alpha and two beta subunits. Binding the beta-subunit is sufficient to inhibit DNA supercoiling.

cvterm.name: fluoroquinolone sensitive parC
cvterm.definition: ParC is a subunit of topoisomerase IV, which decatenates and relaxes DNA to allow access to genes for transcription or translation. Targeting topoisomerase IV inhibits DNA synthesis, and may also lead to double-stranded cell breaks.

cvterm.name: rho transcription terminator factor
cvterm.definition: The rho transcription terminator factor moves along RNA as it is transcribed, unwinding the RNA from the DNA. It is also responsible for recognizing transcription termination pause sites, slowing down RNA polymerase and allowing mRNA to be released.

cvterm.name: rifamycin sensitive beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB)
cvterm.definition: The beta-subunit of RNA polymerase is targeted as a complex. When blocked, RNA strand elongation cannot continue after the first few nucleotides.

cvterm.name: deoxyribonucleic acid
cvterm.definition: Antibiotics can target DNA to cause strand breaks or prevent transcription. The activity of these antibiotics can be context dependent: some antibiotics are converted to an active form only in certain species, while others target DNA as it is being transcribed.

cvterm.name: RNA guanosine binding site
cvterm.definition: RNA intron self-splicing action can be inhibited by antibiotics that target a G-binding site to compete with the guanosine cofactor.

cvterm.name: ribonucleic acid
cvterm.definition: Many types of ribonucleic acids (RNAs) are targeted by antibiotics, including mRNA templates and ribosomal RNA. Some antibiotics target all RNAs and cause strand breaks.

cvterm.name: transcription complex DNA
cvterm.definition: DNA in the transcriptional complex is partially unwound, allowing antibiotics to target exposed bases and prevent DNA transcription.

cvterm.name: anaerobe DNA
cvterm.definition: DNA in anaerobes are targeted by antibiotics that are converted to an active form in the anaerobe environment. For nitroimidazoles, the antibiotic is reduced to a highly oxidative intermediate that causes DNA oxidation and double-stranded breaks.

cvterm.name: 1-deoxy-D-xylulose 5-phosphate reductoisomerase
cvterm.definition: This reductoisomerase is found in an alternate isoprenoid synthase pathway that is mevalonate independent. Isoprenoids are important precursors to many other macromolecules. This non-mevalonate pathway is used by plants and most bacteria, including mycobacteria, but not eukaryotes, allowing for selectivea action. Staphylococcus aureus and some other Gram-positive bacteria use a mevalonate-dependent pathway, and are resistant against 1-deoxy-D-xylose 5-phosphate reductoisomerase inhibitors.

cvterm.name: sulfonamide sensitive dihydropteroate synthase
cvterm.definition: Dihydropteroate synthase catalyzes the conversion of p-aminobenzoic acid to dihydropteroic acid as part of the tetrahydrofolic acid biosynthetic pathway. Tetrahydrofolic acid is essential for folate synthesis, and a precursor of many nucleotides and amino acids. Inhibiting dihydropteroate leads to slow cell death, as bacteria can survive on existing folate storages for a few generations.

cvterm.name: dihydrofolate reductase
cvterm.definition: Dihydrofolate reductase synthesizes the co-enzyme tetrahydrofolic acid, which is also an essential precursor in the de novo synthesis of the DNA nucleotide thymidine.

cvterm.name: mepR
cvterm.definition: MepR is an upstream repressor of MepA in Staphylococcus aureus. It is part of the mepRAB operon.

cvterm.name: mef
cvterm.definition: Mef efflux pumps are MFS-type transporters that confer macrolide resistance in Streptococcus pneumoniae.

cvterm.name: subunit of efflux pump conferring antibiotic resistance
cvterm.definition: Subunits of efflux proteins that pump antibiotic out of a cell to confer resistance.

cvterm.name: beta-lactam sensitive penicillin-binding protein
cvterm.definition: Penicillin-binding proteins (PBPs) are responsible for transpeptidation, joining subunits to form peptidoglycan. They are numbered according to descending molecular weight, and may vary between species. These numbers represent the PBPs of E. coli. Inhibition of the larger PBPs responsible for transpeptidation (1-3) are lethal. Smaller PBPs (4-6) are involed in carboxypeptidation; inhibition of these is non-lethal.

cvterm.name: subunit of gene modulating antibiotic efflux
cvterm.definition: Subunits of genes that directly or indirectly change rates of antibiotic efflux.

cvterm.name: peptide antibiotic resistance gene
cvterm.definition: Genes conferring resistance to peptide antibiotics.

cvterm.name: rgi_colour
cvterm.definition: HTML colour for use by the Resistance Gene Identifier defined using hexadecimal notation (HEX) for the combination of Red, Green, and Blue color values (RGB).

cvterm.name: AbeM
cvterm.definition: AbeM is an multidrug efflux pump found in Acinetobacter baumannii.

cvterm.name: antibiotic sensitive peptidyl transferase (23S rRNA)
cvterm.definition: The bacterial 23S rRNA, at the P site of the 50S subunit, has peptidyl transferase activity and is responsible for peptide synthesis and elongation.

cvterm.name: 16S rRNA (A-site)
cvterm.definition: The 16S rRNA of the 30S ribosomal subunit helps to stabilize the aminoacyl-tRNAs for pairing with the mRNA codons. Some antibiotics (aminoglycosides) that target the 16S rRNA lead to mRNA misreading as well as premature termination. Other antibiotics (tetracyclines) that target the 16S rRNA prevent incoming charged-tRNAs from binding to the ribosome's A-site, stopping elongation.

cvterm.name: 30S ribosomal subunit P-site
cvterm.definition: The P-site of the ribosome binds the peptidyl-tRNA with the growing polypeptide chain. Antibiotics that target the P-site block fMet-tRNA from entering, thus inhibiting peptide elongation.

cvterm.name: 50S ribosomal subunit P-site
cvterm.definition: The P-site of the ribosome binds the peptidyl-tRNA with the growing polypeptide chain, and is a common target for many antibiotics that inhibit the 50S ribosomal subunit. Some antibiotics (oxazolidinones) block the 50S subunit from interacting with the 30S subunit to prevent the formation of the ribosomal complex.
